  <details class="help">
    <summary>How to read this dashboard</summary>
    <div class="help-body">
      <p>This site is a <strong>self-updating literature review</strong>: every day it reads new papers
         that evaluate geospatial foundation models (AlphaEarth, TESSERA, Prithvi, Clay, …) and extracts
         their quantitative results. Every number shown here links back to a paper and a
         <em>verbatim quote</em> from it — nothing is editorialised.</p>
      <dl>
        <dt>Direction <span class="dir dir-better">▲ better</span> <span class="dir dir-worse">▼ worse</span> <span class="dir dir-parity">≈ parity</span></dt>
        <dd>Colours always compare a <strong>foundation model against a task-specific model</strong> — a bespoke
            supervised model built for that exact task, i.e. what a practitioner would otherwise use — on one
            dataset. <em>Better</em> = the foundation model wins, <em>worse</em> = the task-specific model wins,
            <em>parity</em> = effectively equal. Model-vs-model results (e.g. TESSERA vs AlphaEarth) are shown
            in the details but never drive the colours; a cell with only those is left neutral.</dd>
        <dt>Evidence labels</dt>
        <dd><span class="chip chip-consensus">consensus</span> ≥3 papers and ≥80% agree on the direction ·
            <span class="chip chip-contested">contested</span> ≥3 papers but they disagree ·
            <span class="chip chip-thin">thin</span> only 1–2 papers so far ·
            <span class="chip chip-gap">gap</span> nobody has looked yet.</dd>
        <dt>Label regime</dt>
        <dd>How much training data the downstream task used: <em>label-rich</em> (≥75% of labels),
            <em>label-partial</em>, <em>label-scarce</em> (≤10%). Results from different regimes are never mixed,
            because label efficiency is precisely what foundation models promise.</dd>
        <dt>Self-evaluation</dt>
        <dd>The paper's authors helped create the very foundation model they evaluate (checked
            mechanically via author overlap with the model's original paper). Such papers tend to report
            wins — the toggle above excludes them.</dd>
        <dt>Never pooled across datasets</dt>
        <dd>A "consensus" always means papers measured the <em>same dataset</em> under the same conditions —
            never an average of apples and oranges.</dd>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </details>

  <nav id="tabs"></nav>
</header>

<main id="view"></main>

<div id="modal" class="modal hidden">
  <div class="modal-box">
    <button id="modalClose" class="modal-close" aria-label="Close">×</button>
    <h2 id="modalTitle"></h2>
    <p class="modal-hint">Each row is one claim from one paper. The quote underneath is copied verbatim
       from the paper and was mechanically verified to appear in its text.</p>
    <div id="modalBody"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<footer>
  <p>Every number on this site is traceable in ≤2 clicks to a paper and a verbatim supporting quote.
     Updated daily and fully automatic; the underlying data is
     <a href="data.json">one JSON file</a>. Inference is subscription-only via a local CLI;
     this site holds no credentials.</p>
</footer>

